Painesville City Fire Department
· 13 September at 12:44 ·
Fire on Frederic St.
The Painesville City Fire Department with aid from Concord, Painesville Twp. and Fairport fire departments responded to a fire on Frederic ...St on Tuesday September 12th at 1:15 p.m.
First arriving units were greeted with heavy fire from the front of the building. The fire was quickly brought under control and extinguished. No one was home at the time of the fire and the home owner's cat was found safe in the basement after extinguishment. There were no injuries reported as a result of this fire.
Just a note of interest: there were 3 additional EMS calls during the time that units were tied up at the fire and Mentor, Grand River and Painesville Twp. were requested to assist with those calls.

Lake County Sheriff's Office
· 6 June ·
Dispatcher Angela King explains what happens when you call 9-1-1 from your cell phone or home phone
911 state the location of your emergency…….
Hi I’m dispatche...r Angela King and I would like to talk to you today about what happens when you call 911 from your cell phone or home phone.
First, I would like to show you central communications (pause to pan dispatch) we are a division of the Lake County Sheriff’s Office and the primary answering point for all wireless cell phone 911 calls in Lake County. When you call 911 it is important for you to answer my questions so we can get you the help you need. The first thing we ask is what is your location? I will need your address, street name, intersection or business name. If you are on a freeway there are mile markers every 10th of a mile, so that will help us pin point your location.
The next thing we need to know is what is happening. Do you need police help or are you having a fire or medical emergency. Depending on the nature of your emergency we will ask a series of questions, like who is involved, when did this happen, are there injuries, does someone have a weapon and are drugs or alcohol involved. All these questions are meant to help you and keep first responders safe and informed as they respond to help you.
As you can see there are several dispatchers working in central communications ( pause and pan), so while I am asking you these questions, another dispatcher may be sending police, fire or an emergency medical squad to you. A dispatcher is trained to do several things at the same time. We talk on the phone and the radio all while typing information into the computer system.
Dispatchers are also trained to give emergency medical assistance before a squad arrives. So if you are calling for someone that is choking or not breathing or bleeding we can give you step by step directions for the Heimlich maneuver and CPR. So don’t worry if you don’t know how, we will stay on the phone with you until help arrives.
You may never see us, but we are here to help you through possibly the worst day of your life. I am a dispatcher. Dispatcher’s save seconds and seconds save lives.
See more

Ohio Association of Professional Fire Fighters is with Michael Christina Palumbo.
· 24 May ·
It is with a heavy heart that the Ohio Association of Professional Fire Fighters reports the passing of Beachwood Fire Captain Michael Palumbo. Captain Palumbo... passed away after a long battle with occupational brain cancer. Mike was the namesake of Ohio’s Michael Louis Palumbo Jr. Act, which provided presumptive workers compensation for fire fighters diagnosed with occupational cancers.
Mike was a captain with the Beachwood Fire Department and a member of Local 2388 since 1992. He leaves behind his wife of 23 years and 5 children, ranging in age from 8 to 21.
The Palumbo family is asking for privacy during this difficult time. Memorial Service details will be released as they are finalized.
Information will also be posted at https://oapff.org/palumbomemorial/

This morning, Riverside High School hosted a new event called Stay in Your Lane, which was a real, interactive, intensive program to educate students about the ...dangers and consequences of drinking and driving.
Seniors from Madison, Fairport Harbor and Kirtland high schools were also in attendance to experience this program which began with a mock crash scene and then moved into a series of speakers who have been personally affected by drunk driving. The event ended with a “Walk of Remembrance” to honor local people who have been lost in drunk driving accidents.
Thank you to guest speakers Matthew Rupert, Aaron Cooksey, Ohio State Highway Patrol Trooper Detmer & Chagrin Falls Police Officer Dick Goldsmith.

Painesville Township Fire Department shared The Western Reserve Fire Museum and Education Center's album.
· 18 April ·

+9
The Western Reserve Fire Museum and Education Center added 12 new photos to the album Painesville Township FD.
· 18 April ·
A look at Painesville Township and their 20th Century fire apparatus. This 1956 Pirsch was operated by Painesville City Fire Department until the township f...ire department was established in 1966. This 1983 photo shows Station 1 with a 1972 Young/Ford pumper and a 1970 Pierce/Oshkosh/ Pitman Snorkel. Not many Youngs in this area from the Lackawana, NY builder. Next were a 1976 Towers/Ford pumper for No. 1 and a 1978 Towers/Ford for No. 2. Towers (St. Louis) had a very interesting pump panel arrangement. Also not many Towers in NE Ohio. Next pumper was a 1986 Towers/Ford front mount. In 1993 PTFD acquired a New Lexington/Spartan pumper (built in Rockland, PA) and in 1997 a Ferrara/Spartan 75ft quint with an RK aerial ladder. This 1989 photo shows PTFD with an ex Lubrizol 1961 Fire Boss/Ford 3400lb dry powder unit. The PTFD Fireman's Association acquired a 1926 Ahrens-Fox Piston pumper ex Winchester, MA (northern suburb of Boston).
Paul Nelson, Historian

Painesville City Fire Department added 3 new photos.
· 17 February ·
ANIMAL RESCUE
The Painesville City Fire Department was called to area of the old Coe Manufacturing on Bank Street around 3:30 p.m. by the Painesville Police Dep...artment for a dog that had somehow ended up about 30 feet down the embankment. The department, with assistance from Painesville Twp. Fire Department, initiated a rope rescue and were successful in retrieving the dog and bringing it to safety.
The dog had broken free of its tether about 4 hours earlier and when we reached it we found the chain was tangled in the brush. The dog was rescued without injury but quite cold.
We must also thank the Lake County Dog Warden's office for providing a warden to assist us once the dog was rescued. They took control of the dog and returned it to its owner.

Painesville Township Fire Department updated their status.
· 12 February ·
.
.
.
Follow up on the laced marijuana: The people involved in these incidents later admitted to the use of other drugs, in addition to smoking marijuana. Lab results found no evidence of laced marijuana. Lab results did find crack cocaine and other drugs in the residence. Sometimes people are not honest with us about what they have taken or used. We treat based on symptoms and what we are told might be wrong. We decided to post the notice on possible tainted marijuana based on the best interest of our community. We see too many people die of opiate related incidents. In 2016, we administered 116 doses of Narcan, 3 deaths in one weekend from opiate use. Thank you for your understanding.

Chase is raising money for the Radiothon benefiting Rainbow Children's Hospital. We will have a collection jar at Station 1 at 55 Nye Rd. until this Thursday. Please stop by with any donation or spare change and help Chase beat his collection record from last year.
"My son Chase has had a special place in his heart for UH Rainbow ever since they saved his little sister Gabby's life 5 years ago. Gabby contracted a rare antibody in her blood at birth that put her into heart f...ailure. At just 2 weeks old she was fighting for her life. Chase was 2.5 years old and would visit his sister every day. He felt the love and generosity of the doctors, nurses, and staff that filled the unit his sister was "living in".
Chase never forgot the feelings he had from that experience and he always told stories about how Rainbow saved his baby sister! Since then, Chase has also become a patient of the Endocronology department. He's strong, positive boy, with a will to make a difference! He raises money throughout the year for Radiothon each December and hopes to beat his own earnings each time. Chase is always thinking of ways to raise as much money as he can "for the kids". His love for Rainbow is so deep!” – Laura Gunnoe

Painesville Township Fire Department added 2 new photos.
· 7 September 2016 ·
.
.
.
Great News: We were awarded a FEMA Assistance to Firefighter Grant to replace the aerial truck. The grant is for $622,728.00 with a 10% local match of $62,272.00. We intend to use this vehicle to replace 2 vehicles in our fleet. About 3 years ago our 1998 75 ft Aerial failed its annual structural testing. The cost to repair was around $250,000, we did not feel the investment in a vehicle that old was wise, the truck had also been giving us electrical problems. We elected... to try to obtain a FEMA Assistance to Fire Fighters Grant to off set the cost of a new truck. We applied for several years, this was the last year we felt we could apply before making the purchase on our own.
We had been relying on other departments for an aerial truck capability. Given the number of industrial complex's and commercial areas we should have an aerial device of our own. We have had several industrial fires were we had to wait for the mutual aid truck to get there before we could deal with the fire. Our ISO Fire Insurance rating is based on us having an aerial device. We now plan to retire our 1994 New Lexington pumper and replace the aerial truck with one truck.
The type of truck we are getting is called a Quint. We use the term Quint because the truck has 5 functions: it can carries water, it can pump water, it will carry hose, it carries ground ladders and it has an aerial device on it. The most effective way to use a quint is have it run first out on fire calls, it would be used to attack a fire, have fire hose deployed, etc. The use of the aerial ladder would be secondary function. In using this concept we don’t need the 4th pumper in the fleet. We would still have a spare pumper available. We feel this plan is appropriate considering our fiscal situation and will not compromise our capability to serve the community. If you want to know more please email me, and I will provide you with more information. Firechief@Painesvilletwp.com
See more

Today we presented a mock crash to stress the importance of safe driving and the terrible consequences of poor choices

· 15 May 2014 ·
.

Great news...The Painesville Township Fire Department has upgrade our ISO rating (a factor that determines your fire insurance rates). We are now rated a Class 3/3X from a 5/9. The best any department can be rated is a Class 1 the worst would be a Class 10. Check with your fire insurance carrier to adjust your ISO risk rating. More to follow, we will be posting the complete report on our Township web site

Don't forget to set your clocks back 1 hour this evening. Also when setting the clocks back we should always remember to change the batteries in our homes smoke detectors. If you your home does not have smoke detectors or you need assistance changing the batteries, please feel free at any time to contact any one of our three stations and we will be more than happy to come out and help. Enjoy the extra hour of sleep!
